Handling missing values

We define a function to replace specific values with NA based on predefined rules and apply these rules to our dataset. The rules list can always be expended without changing the function.

replace_values_with_na_mutate <- function(df, rules) {
  df %>%
    mutate(across(
      .cols = names(rules),
      .fns = ~ if_else(. %in% rules[[cur_column()]], NA_real_, .)
    ))
}

rules <- list(
  Age = c(9999),
  TBV = c(9999),
  TBV_Ratio = c(9999),
  Mutation = c(9999),
  GMV = c(9999),
  ICV = c(9999)
)

Subset data

We’ll create subsets of our dataset based on the Disease column to separate DMD (patients with disease) and HC (healthy control patients). We also handle the missing values with the replace_values_with_na_mutate function based on our defined rules.

dmd <- dataset[dataset$Disease == 1, ]
hc <- dataset[dataset$Disease == 0, ]

dmd <- replace_values_with_na_mutate(dmd, rules)
hc <- replace_values_with_na_mutate(hc, rules)

Combine DMD and HC datasets

Here we combine the DMD and HC datasets to perform inferential statistics on the TBV ratio between the two groups. With the is.finite function, we filter out any missing values in the Age and TBV columns. We then create a new column group to identify the patients as either DMD or HC.

# Combine DMD and HC datasets
all_patients <- rbind(dmd, hc)
all_patients <- all_patients %>%
  mutate(group = ifelse(Disease == 1, "DMD", "HC")) %>%
  filter(is.finite(Age), is.finite(TBV))

Age Group Analysis

We want to categorize patients into different age groups based on the visit number to understand the age distribution of patients. We will categorize patients into the following age groups: 0 - 5 years old, 6 - 12 years old, 13 - 19 years old, 20 - 25 years old, and 26+ years old.

Categorize patients into different age groups based on the visit number using the mutate and case_when functions to get the age distrubution of the patients.

# categorize_age function to categorize patients into different age groups
categorize_age <- function(age) {
  age <- round(age) # Round the age to the nearest whole number
  case_when(
    is.na(age) ~ NA_character_, # Explicitly handle NA values
    age <= 5 ~ "0 - 5 years old",
    age <= 12 ~ "6 - 12 years old",
    age <= 19 ~ "13 - 19 years old",
    age <= 25 ~ "20 - 25 years old",
    age >= 26 ~ "26+ years old",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  )
}
Note

Age Groups: Defined as “0 - 5 years old,” “6 - 12 years old,” “13 - 19 years old,” “20 - 25 years old,” and “26+ years old.”

Here we define a function to display the number of patients in each age group and the percentage of patients in each group.

# display_age_groups function to display the number of patients in each age group and the percentage of patients in each group
display_age_groups <- function(df, group_name) {
  df <- df %>% mutate(age_group = categorize_age(Age))
  age_groups <- c("0 - 5 years old", "6 - 12 years old", "13 - 19 years old", "20 - 25 years old", "26+ years old")
  total_patients <- nrow(df)
  
  message(group_name, " patients by age group:")
  for (age_group in age_groups) {
    count <- nrow(df[df$age_group == age_group, ])
    percentage <- round(100 / total_patients * count, 1)
    message(sprintf("%s: %d (%.1f%%)", age_group, count, percentage))
  }
}
Note

Percentage calculation: (100 / total number of patients) * number of patients in each age group

Mutation Group analysis

We will analyze the mutation group for both DMD and HC patients to determine the number of patients in each group.

Assign patients to mutation groups based on the Mutation column

# categorize_mutation function to categorize patients into different mutation groups
categorize_mutation <- function(mutation) {
  case_when(
    mutation == 0 ~ "Healthy",
    mutation == 1 ~ "Proximal",
    mutation == 2 ~ "Distal",
    mutation == 3 ~ "Unknown",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  )
}

Count the number of patients in each mutation group and percentage

Note

We calculate the percentage of patients in each mutation group for both DMD and HC groups. The percentage is calculated as (100 / total number of patients) * number of patients in each mutation group.

Note

Mutation Groups: Defined as “Healthy,” “Proximal,” “Distal,” and “Unknown.”

mutation_groups <- c("Healthy", "Proximal", "Distal", "Unknown")

display_mutation_groups <- function(df, group_name) {
  df <- df %>% mutate(mutation_group = categorize_mutation(Mutation))
  
  total_patients <- nrow(df)
  
  message(group_name, " patients by mutation group:")
  for (group in mutation_groups) {
    count <- sum(df$mutation_group == group, na.rm = TRUE)
    percentage <- round(100 / total_patients * count, 1)
    message(sprintf("%s: %d (%.1f%%)", group, count, percentage))
  }
}
  • DMD
  • HC
dmd_mutation <- dmd %>% mutate(mutation_group = categorize_mutation(Mutation))
display_mutation_groups(dmd_mutation, "DMD")

Distal: 35 (41.7%)

Assign patients to corticosteroid groups based on the Corticosteroid column

categorize_corticosteroid <- function(corticosteroid) {
  case_when(
    is.na(corticosteroid) ~ NA_character_,
    corticosteroid == 0 ~ "No",
    corticosteroid == 1 ~ "Yes",
    corticosteroid == 2 ~ "Unknown",
    TRUE ~ "Other"
  )
}

Calculate the percentage of patients in each corticosteroid group

We calculate the percentage of patients in each corticosteroid group for both DMD and HC groups. The percentage is calculated as (100 / total number of patients) * number of patients in each corticosteroid group.

display_group_numbers <- function(df, group_name, group_column) {
  if (!group_column %in% names(df)) {
    stop(paste("Column", group_column, "does not exist in the dataframe."))
  }
  
  df <- df %>% filter(!is.na(!!sym(group_column)))
  total_patients <- nrow(df)
  
  groups <- unique(df[[group_column]])
  
  # Calculate group percentages and output the results
  group_counts <- df %>%
    count(!!sym(group_column)) %>%
    mutate(percentage = round(100 / sum(n) * n, 1))
  
  message(group_name, " patients by ", group_column, ":")
  print(group_counts)
}

With model.fit1 we will fit a linear mixed-effect model to predict the TBV ratio based on the age, age squared and corrected for covariance scannertype and group of the patients. We will then print the summary of the model to assess the model fit.

So, to explain, with model.fit1 we will fit a linear mixed-effect model aimed at predicting the Total Brain Volume (TBV) ratio. This model includes Age and Age2 as predictors, while controlling the covariance introduced by Scannertype and group of the patients. The random intercept for ID accounts for individual variability for more accurate predictions by considering each patient’s unique baseline characteristics.

model.fit1 <- lmer(TBV_Ratio ~ (1 | ID) + Age + Age2 + group + (group * Age) + (group * Age2) + Scannertype + (1 | Scannertype), data = all_patients)

ANOVA Test

We will perform a series of ANOVA tests. ANOVA (Analysis of Variance) helps to compare nested models to determine if adding complexity to the model results in a significantly better fit. Specifically, we will use three ANOVA tests to evaluate different aspects of model complexity:

  • ANOVA Test 1
  • ANOVA Test 2
  • ANOVA Test 3

Compares model.fit0 and model.fit. This test will help us determine whether including group and its interaction terms with Age and Age^2 provides a significant improvement in model fit compared to the baseline model (model.fit0), which only includes Age, Age^2, and Scannertype as predictors.

Scatterplot of TBV Ratio vs Age

Here we are looking at the relationship between age and total brain volume TBV in two groups of patients: DMD (Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy) and HC (healthy controls). We want to understand if there is any apparent trend in brain volume across different ages, and if such a trend differs between the two groups.

To assess the overall trend in the data, we include a linear regression line (in black) that fits all the data points. This line represents the general direction and strength of the relationship between age and brain volume across both groups combined. By using a linear model (method = “lm”), we can see if there is an increasing or decreasing trend of TBV with age.

# Scatterplot of TBV ratio vs Age
p <- ggplot(all_patients, aes(x = Age, y = TBV, color = group)) +

  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Brain Volume", x = "Age", y = "TBV (cm³)", color = "Group") +

  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black") +

Here we are examining the the relationship between age and total brain volume TBV in patients from two distinct groups: DMD (Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy) and HC (healthy controls) to visualize whether there are any age-related trends in brain volume and how these trends may differ between the two groups.

We add LOESS lines for each group, which provide a locally smoothed fit to the data. The lines identify non-linear trends in TBV with respect to age, to see how brain volume changes over time for each group and whether these changes differ between groups. By using LOESS, we get a more flexible model compared to linear regression, as it can capture more subtle patterns that a straight line might miss.

The scatterplot is color-coded by group (DMD vs. HC) to distinguish between the two groups, and the LOESS lines are colored red for DMD and green for HC. This color scheme helps to visually separate the groups and identify any differences in the relationship between age and TBV.

# Scatterplot of TBV ratio vs Age with separate LOESS lines for each group
p <- ggplot(all_patients, aes(x = Age, y = TBV, color = group)) +
  geom_point(na.rm = TRUE) +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Brain Volume with LOESS Lines", x = "Age", y = "TBV (cm³)", color = "Group") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  geom_smooth(data = subset(all_patients, group == "DMD"), method = "loess", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  geom_smooth(data = subset(all_patients, group == "HC"), method = "loess", se = FALSE, color = "green") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("DMD" = "red", "HC" = "green")) +

Data cleaning

To ensure the data is clean and ready for analysis because missing or non-finite values can lead to misleading results or errors in subsequent analyses and visualizations. The following code filters out rows where either Age or TBV is missing (NA) or non-finite (e.g., Inf, -Inf, NaN). The cleaned data will be used for further analysis and plotting.

# Filter out rows with missing or non-finite values in Age and TBV columns
dmd <- dmd %>% filter(!is.na(Age) & !is.na(TBV) & is.finite(Age) & is.finite(TBV))
hc <- hc %>% filter(!is.na(Age) & !is.na(TBV) & is.finite(Age) & is.finite(TBV))

Linear Regression Analysis

Here we will perform a linear regression analysis to predict the brain volume based on the age and group of the patients.

clean_data <- all_patients[is.finite(all_patients$Age) & is.finite(all_patients$TBV), ]
model <- lm(TBV ~ Age, data = clean_data)
plot(all_patients$Age, all_patients$TBV, xlab = "Age", ylab = "TBV (cm³)", pch = 20, col = "grey35")
# GLM model to predict the brain volume based on the age and group
# y = B0 + B1 * x1 + B2 * x2 + B3 * x1 * x2
# y = B0 + B1 * x1 + B2 * x2 + B3 * Bn * Xn + e
# B1 * x1 is the central determinent of the model
# B2 * x2 are the covariants of the model
model <- lm(TBV ~ Age, data = dmd)
model2 <- lm(TBV ~ Age, data = hc)
print(summary(model))

Repeated Measures

# Scatter plot of GMV and TBV ratio with repeated measures
baseplot_repeated_measures <- ggplot(all_patients, aes(x = Age, y = GMV, color = group)) +
  
  geom_point(data = dmd_patients_first_visit %>% filter(!is.na(Age) & is.finite(Age)), 
             aes(x = Age, y = GMV, color = "DMD")) +
  geom_point(data = dmd_patients_second_visit %>% filter(!is.na(Age) & is.finite(Age)), 
             aes(x = Age, y = GMV, color = "DMD")) +
  geom_line(data = dmd %>% filter(!is.na(Age) & !is.na(GMV) & is.finite(Age) & is.finite(GMV)), 
            aes(x = Age, y = GMV, group = ID, color = "DMD"), linetype = "solid") +
  
  geom_point(data = hc_patients_first_visit %>% filter(!is.na(Age) & is.finite(Age)), 
             aes(x = Age, y = GMV, color = "HC")) +
  geom_point(data = hc_patients_second_visit %>% filter(!is.na(Age) & is.finite(Age)), 
             aes(x = Age, y = GMV, color = "HC")) +
  geom_line(data = hc %>% filter(!is.na(Age) & !is.na(GMV) & is.finite(Age) & is.finite(GMV)), 
            aes(x = Age, y = GMV, group = ID, color = "HC"), linetype = "solid") +
  
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, aes(fill = group)) +
  
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Group") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Group") +
  
  labs(title = "GMV over Age with Repeated Measures", x = "Age", y = "GMV", color = "Group") +
  theme_bw()

p <- ggplotly(baseplot_repeated_measures)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
